455":"1455","1485":"1485","1550":"1550","1460":"1460","1480":"1480","22 Aug 1485":"22 August 1485","Southwick, Hampshire, England":"Southwick, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom","Southwick, Southhampton, England":"Southwick, Sussex, England","Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, England","Bosworth Field, Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Barnham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from either of the places named  <i>Barnham</i>, in Suffolk and Sussex, or from  <i>Barnham Broom</i> in Norfolk. Each of these place-names is from the Old English male personal name  <i>Beorn</i> or  <i>Beorna</i>, +  <i>hām</i> ‘large farming estate’."],"variants":[{"name":"Barnum","meanings":["Altered form of English <b>Barnham</b>: habitational name from any of the places called Barnham in Suffolk and West Sussex, or <i>Barnham Broom</i> in Norfolk, all of which were named with the male personal name <i>Beorn</i> or <i>Beorna</i> + Old English <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Elizabeth Barnham was born in 1460, in Southwick, Hampshire, England. She married Sir Nicholas Southwick in 1480, in Southwick, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1510, in Hampshire, England, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1460–1510":"1460–1510","1455–1485":"1455–1485","1480–1550":"1480–1550","1510":"1510","1455":"1455","1485":"1485","1550":"1550","1460":"1460","1480":"1480","22 Aug 1485":"22. august 1485","Southwick, Hampshire, England":"Southwick, Hampshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Southwick, Southhampton, England":"Southwick, Sussex, England","Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, England","Bosworth Field, Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1460–1510":"1460–1510","1455–1485":"1455–1485","1480–1550":"1480–1550","1510":"1510","1455":"1455","1485":"1485","1550":"1550","1460":"1460","1480":"1480","22 Aug 1485":"22. elokuuta 1485","Southwick, Hampshire, England":"Southwick, Hampshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Southwick, Southhampton, England":"Southwick, Sussex, England","Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, England","Bosworth Field, Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1460–1510":"1460–1510","1455–1485":"1455–1485","1480–1550":"1480–1550","1510":"1510","1455":"1455","1485":"1485","1550":"1550","1460":"1460","1480":"1480","22 Aug 1485":"22 août 1485","Southwick, Hampshire, England":"Southwick, Hampshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Southwick, Southhampton, England":"Southwick, Sussex, Angleterre","Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, Angleterre","Bosworth